      {
        "id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2001_Solutions_2001s_page_001_6",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Note: Richard Stanley points out the following noninductive argument. Put f(x) = П½=1 x+ 2k)/(2k + 1); then the coefficient of x' in f(x) is the probability of getting exactly i heads. Thus the desired number is (f(1)- f(-1))/2, and both values of f can be computed directly: f(1) = 1, and",
