    "member_count": 2,
    "elements": [
      {
        "id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2001_Solutions_2001s_page_001_19",
        "observed_type": "list_item",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "A-5 Suppose a\"+1 - (a + 1)\" = 2001. Notice that a\"+1 + (a + 1)\" - 1 is a multiple of a; thus a divides 2002 = 2x7 × 11 × 13.",
        "bbox": [
          0.5244360892744201,
          0.6408730158466791,
          0.9172932291757762,
          0.6834570467334161
        ],
        "order": 17
      },
      {
        "id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2001_Solutions_2001s_page_001_20",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Since 2001 is divisible by 3, we must have a = 1 (mod 3), otherwise one of alt! and (a + 1)\" is a multiple of 3 and the other is not, so their difference cannot be divisible by 3. Now a\"+1 = 1 (mod 3), so we must have (a + 1)\" = 1 (mod 3), which forces n to be even, and in particular at least 2.",
        "bbox": [
          0.556349230208115,
          0.690406976858643,
          0.9210526389119592,
          0.7748015873522592
        ],
        "order": 18
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "eu_id": "EU-0009",
    "kind": "text_cluster_panel",
    "page": "exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2001_Solutions_2001s_page_001",
    "primary_id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2001_Solutions_2001s_page_001_10",
    "source": "text_cluster",
    "member_count": 1,
    "elements": [
      {
        "id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2001_Solutions_2001s_page_001_10",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Next, suppose that the subset contains two elements; then we can take it to be one of {Vm V2}, {V2+ Vm} or {#(Vm + V2)}. In all cases, the sum and the product of the elements of the subset must be a rational number. In the first case, this means 2Vm € Q, so m is a perfect square. In the second case, we have 2V2 € Q, contradiction. In the third case, we have (Vm + V2)? € Q, or m + 2 + 2V 2m € Q, which means that m is twice a perfect square.",
        "bbox": [
          0.12767660014240578,
          0.7194767439785242,
          0.49067075644321656,
          0.8531976745463957
        ],
        "order": 19
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "eu_id": "EU-0010",
    "kind": "text_cluster_panel",
    "page": "exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2001_Solutions_2001s_page_001",
    "primary_id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2001_Solutions_2001s_page_001_21",
    "source": "text_cluster",
    "member_count": 1,
    "elements": [
      {
        "id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2001_Solutions_2001s_page_001_21",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "If a is even, then a\"+1 - (a + 1)\"= -(a + 1)\" (mod 4). Since n is even, -(a + 1)\" = -1 (mod 4). Since 2001 = 1 (mod 4), this is impossible. Thus a is odd, and so must divide 1001 = 7 × 11 × 13. Moreover, a\"+1 -(a+ 1)\" = a (mod 4), so a = 1 (mod 4).",
        "bbox": [
          0.5582706723584041,
          0.7790178570766289,
          0.9210526343066961,
          0.8531976740995691
        ],
        "order": 20
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "eu_id": "EU-0011",
    "kind": "text_cluster_panel",
    "page": "exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2001_Solutions_2001s_page_001",
    "primary_id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2001_Solutions_2001s_page_001_11",
    "source": "text_cluster",
    "member_count": 1,
    "elements": [
      {
        "id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2001_Solutions_2001s_page_001_11",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "We conclude that Pm (x) factors into two nonconstant polynomials over the integers if and only if m is either a square or twice a square.",
        "bbox": [
          0.12781955179573123,
          0.8590116277902974,
          0.4906015054724391,
          0.9011627900506035
        ],
        "order": 21
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "eu_id": "EU-0012",
    "kind": "text_cluster_panel",
    "page": "exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2001_Solutions_2001s_page_001",
    "primary_id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2001_Solutions_2001s_page_001_22",
    "source": "text_cluster",
    "member_count": 1,
    "elements": [
      {
        "id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2001_Solutions_2001s_page_001_22",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Of the divisors of 7 × 11 x 13, those congruent to 1 mod 3 are precisely those not divisible by 11 (since 7 and 13 are both congruent to 1 mod 3). Thus a divides 7 × 13. Now a = 1 (mod 4) is only possible if a divides 13.",
        "bbox": [
          0.5582706707919883,
          0.8590116279174775,
          0.9210526312756813,
          0.91569767420758
        ],
        "order": 22
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "eu_id": "EU-0013",
    "kind": "text_cluster_panel",
    "page": "exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2001_Solutions_2001s_page_001",
    "primary_id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2001_Solutions_2001s_page_001_12",
